<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Re: Deregulation Bill</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Pennine Way Association – Written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">I would like to give my total support to the Yorkshire Dales Green Lanes Alliance on their proposal to include two clauses in the above Bill.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The first relates to ‘unsealed’ (i.e. not sealed with tarmac or concrete) Ways.  Green Lanes, including those on the Pennine Way are generally unsealed and are prone to misuse by recreational motor vehicles and motor bikes (see attached photographs of such a Byway on the Pennine Way (before and after vehicle damage).  What we would like to see is there to be a distinction between ‘unsealed’ and ‘sealed’ Ways.  We would like a clause included in the bill to ensure that all unsealed Byways Open to All Traffic (BOATs) and all unsealed Unclassified Country Roads (UCRs) should be recognised as not being part of the ordinary roads network, and that they should be re-classified as Restricted Byways.  It should be noted that Restricted Byways have rights of way for pedestrians, horses, horse-drawn carriages, pedal cyclists, and motor vehicles needed for access to premises (e.g. farm vehicles) but they are not for recreational vehicles.  This would prevent misuse and damage to these Ways which cost tens of thousands of </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">taxpayers</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> money to repair each incident and spoils the Way for non vehicular users such as walkers and cyclists.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Secondly, under current legislation, a Local Authority can turn down a request for imposing a Traffic Regulation Order [TRO] (the legal mechanism which prohibits non-essential motor vehicles from using Green Lanes), with no grounds for appeal.  We would like the bill to include a provision such that when a Local Authority declines to impose a TRO which is widely supported by the public, that there should be a right of appeal, either to an independent inspector or a magistrate.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Chris </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Sainty</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Chairman</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Pennine Way Association</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">5 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>